Investigating Significance II: v3

Ben Wheeler

April 6, 2017

Investigating All Candidates in a Race as a single population

update: 10-23-2017 * Updated observation columns for variables. (111-117) instead of 89-

Purpose

The purpose of this document is to make progress in determining significance of Twitter Percentages for Republicans. This analysis uses a different data structure than we have been using, it takes advantage of using each candidate as a single observation, but treats all candidates in all counties as a population. There are 62 counties in New York, of them all of them had tweets that were placed within their boundaries. This dataset includes 62 observations for each candidate. One observation for each county. Thus the republican dataset includes 186 observations.

Key Takeaways

  • All Subsets are significant when run with any characteristics.
  • The population is significant, however the individuals are not.
  • Is the population significant because of underlying issues with using everyone from the same race, aka they are all reliant on each other. I still can’t answer this question.

Determine ability to use Linear Regression

Assumptions are as follows:
  • Linear relationship
  • Multivariate normality
  • No or little multicollinearity
  • No auto-correlation
  • Homoscedasticity

Also there is a rule of thumb of 20 records in order to conduct linear regression. http://www.statisticssolutions.com/assumptions-of-linear-regression/

http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/correlation-test-between-two-variables-in-r - Checking the Correlation between two variables, how do I test the correlation… - potentially use rank() to rank and then do a rho or a spearman correlation.

Define Function to Print out Statistics and Plot Data

gloop <- function(n,data.in,subset1,subset2,subset3,label.main,label.X, label.Y){
    RegModel.Model <- lm(Candidate_VS~data.in[,n], data=data.in)
    Test <- summary(RegModel.Model)
    Coef  <- Test[4]
    rvals <- c(Test[9],Test[8])
    xlim <- c(0,1)
    ylim <- c(0,1)
      plot(subset1$Candidate_VS,subset1[,n],xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, col='Blue',
           xlab=label.X,
           ylab =label.Y,
           main = label.main)
      points(subset2$Candidate_VS,subset2[,n],xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, col='Green')
      points(subset3$Candidate_VS,subset3[,n],xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, col='Red')
      legend("right", 
             legend=c("Trump", "Kasich","Cruz"),
                col=c("blue","Green","red"), 
                pch=1, cex=0.8, inset =.01, box.lty=1)
      var1 <- substr(toString(rvals[2]),1,5)
      var2 <- substr(toString(rvals[1]),1,5)
      text(0.95,0.05,label=paste("R2:",var1))
      text(0.923,0.1,label=paste("R2_adj:",var2))
    return(list(
      stats=c(Coef,rvals),
      model=RegModel.Model
    ))      
}
gloop2 <- function(n,data.in,subset1,subset2,label.main,label.X, label.Y,cand1,cand2){
    RegModel.Model <- lm(Candidate_VS~data.in[,n], data=data.in)
    Test <- summary(RegModel.Model)
    Coef  <- Test[4]
    rvals <- c(Test[9],Test[8])
    xlim <- c(0,1)
    ylim <- c(0,1)
      plot(subset1$Candidate_VS,subset1[,n],xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, col='Blue',
           xlab=label.X,
           ylab =label.Y,
           main = label.main)
      points(subset2$Candidate_VS,subset2[,n],xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, col='Red')
      legend("right", 
             legend=c(cand1, cand2),
                col=c("blue","red"), 
                pch=1, cex=0.8, inset =.01, box.lty=1)
      var1 <- substr(toString(rvals[2]),1,5)
      var2 <- substr(toString(rvals[1]),1,5)
      text(0.95,0.05,label=paste("R2:",var1))
      text(0.923,0.1,label=paste("R2_adj:",var2))
    return(list(
      stats=c(Coef,rvals),
      model=RegModel.Model
    ))      
}
